description.plain:
“Sofia” is third single from Clairo’s debut album, Immunity. “Sofia” is about Clairo’s first crushes on women such as director Sofia Coppola or actress Sofia Vergara. In this song she talks about a period of time where she was discovering her sexuality. Clairo describes “Sofia” as an “empowering” track in an interview with Coup de Main, stating:

It was important to me that “Sofia” was celebratory because it should be celebrated. At the end of the day it’s something that I’m really proud of and I’m really happy that I can look at the world that way – that I can find beauty in women.

annotations: Honey, I don’t want it to fade

Clairo wants this honeymoon phase of their love to stay strong. She wants her feelings to be reciprocated, and doesn’t want this relationship to “fade” away.

In an interview with Coup de Main, Clairo describes challenges,

I feel like it’s unhealthy to constantly feel like you have to win someone over in a relationship. […] They’re not texting you back, they’re not hanging out with you, they’re not showing you that they care – mean you know it’s not right!

I just wanna say
 How I love you with your hair down

Women are beautiful and I’ve been with a girl that just looked so good with her hair down. I was like, ‘Oh my god, please don’t ever put your hair up again. You look amazing!’ Just things like that. When she would have her hair up and then she would take it out, I’d be like, ‘OH MY GOD.’

– Clairo, Coup De Main Magazine
Sofia, know that you and I

The “Sofia” that Clairo refers to in her lyrics are her “first ever crushes”, Sofia Coppola and Sofia Vergara. Clairo explained to Twitter that she chose to name the song after these women to celebrate the discovery, delivering it in “cheesy/corny” manner, typically found in songs where “you profess your love.”

When speaking to NME Claire commented on her reaction to receiving the demo back:

I was able to jump around my room about how happy I was that I had a crush on Sofia Coppola.

In an interview with Out in April 2019, Clairo revealed that she’s “still not really sure what [her] sexuality is, but [she does] know that it’s not straight.”
There’s things that I know could get in the way

In this line, Clairo is referring to all the struggles she might face in this relationship. Such as the homophobic reactions to the couple, as well as their own internalized stereotypes about same-sex relationships.

She shared on Twitter:

[This is about the] fear of what others' think, [and] internalized feelings about sexuality, etc.

Clairo further describes struggles within the LGBTQ+ community in her interview with Coup de Main, stating:

I’m not the first person that should have a platform when it comes to talking about sexuality, but I’m here to recognize all of the people that go through really terrible things every day just to be able to express that about themselves way more than I do.

I think we could do it if we tried
 If only to say you’re mine

Here Clairo is saying that if both of them wouldn’t be afraid of speaking out about their feelings to each other, this relationship could work.

She explained the meaning of these lines on Twitter saying:

[The lines are about] knowing what you want, but feeling scared to reach out for it. But if you tried, you could have it.

The song is specifically about the difficulty of same-sex relationships. Clairo explains that she knows this relationship would be harder because of the societal stigma, but she believes in them together nevertheless.

The line that compares the feelings couple have to a crime is a reference to the fact that in many countries homosexuality is illegal and LGBTQ+ people are still criminalized.

annotations: Oh, pink flowers grow from my skin
This could possibly be a reference to the fictional disease ‘hanaki’, when if in a situation of unrequited love, flowers grow inside the person, eventually growing out of the skin.
You look so nice in your shirt

this is what the singer wants to say but cant because they swallowed the bubblegum in other words they cant confess their feelings, the sad part is that if it was a guy they were confessing their feelings to it probably would make the guy’s whole year
I didn’t kiss you
She doesn’t kiss her

I’d do anything for you
 But would you do that for me, too?

We all would do anything for our crush/girlfriend/boyfriend.
But does he/she think the same way we do?
It’s sad because it just hurts
yeah
Pink flowers grow from my skin

Pink is a soft colour which is often found in baby girls bedrooms implying youth and innocence. By it “growing from my skin”shows a new start and the germination of something new in life. This creates  hope and apprehension.
Bubble gum down my throat and it’s a curse

This could reference a bad feeling or sentence the singer always has in their throat, and they can’t get rid of it or say it, therefore, making it a curse.

Edit: It could also be a metaphor for the hard truth the singer has to “swallow.”
Pepto Bismol veins and I grin

Pepto-Bismol (Bismuth Subsalicylate) is a brand of medicine used to treat upset stomachs and/or diarrhea, among a variety of other symptoms. It comes in a trademark pink color and is often associated to bubblegum because of its similar colors and allegedly similar taste.

’Cause I swallowed the bubble gum
 Oh, and these seven years will be pretty dumb

It’s often said that bubble gum takes seven years to fully digest in your stomach. In reality, that’s not true at all. After few days bubble gum leaves our bodies as it should.

The bubble gum in this song could be a metaphor for a negative moment in life that lingers on, just as the common belief with gum inside our bodies. It’s also interesting how she doesn’t mention swallowing the gum accidentally, she even says “it’s a curse”. She could doing this willingly whilst knowing it could hurt her to describe the uncertainty of love.

description.plain:
“Bags” is the first single from Clairo’s debut album Immunity. It was first teased on May 24, 2019, with Clairo announcing that the track would be available at midnight.

Co-produced by Rostam, the song sheds the hazy, lo-fi, aesthetic prevalent in Clairo’s previous work. Instead, the track is brighter and more focused, embracing soft guitar, wavy synths, and twinkling piano, bringing a new sheen to Clairo’s music. “Bags” was inspired by Clairo’s first time with a girl,  lyrically presenting a narrative where she struggles to tell her love interest that she’s crushing on them, hard.

In October 2019, Pitchfork ranked the song at #123 in their “The 200 Best Songs of the 2010s” list.

annotations: Know you’d make fun of me

In her interview with I-D, Clairo talks about her experience in writing this album, particularly in reference to her sexuality and how as a teenager she was afraid that she’d come out whilst at a sleepover talking in her sleep or as she was getting her wisdom teeth pulled. Whilst this fear about coming out manifested itself in a variety of ways, she also talks about how supportive her family are and that she largely feels confident and capable after coming out.
Can you see me using everything to hold back?

Clairo talks about how she remembers sitting in the passenger seat of a car and realising for the first time that she’s “crushing hard on the girl next to her.” She speaks about how she was wondering whether the feeling was mutual, although making the first move seemed too much like a risk. This line highlights how she has a desire to explore her feelings for the first time, although is nervous about potentially ruining the moment and the timing.

Pour your glass of wine
 Mitchell told me I should be just fine (Yeah)
 Cases under the bed

Mitchell is Joni Mitchell. So, pour your glass of wine, Mitchell. Joni Mitchell told me I’ll be just fine, cases under the bed. Spill it open, let it rush to my head. It’s an illusion to “A Case of You” by Joni Mitchell, and me and this person had been driving around listening to Joni Mitchell, but also Joni Mitchell is like a very important person to me. I just grew up listening to a lot of Joni Mitchell through my mom. That whole record is very special to me, and I think her writing is one of my absolute favorites, and you know, being able to share that with another person, driving around and listening to “A Case of You” was cool for me. It was a sweet moment. It’s like when you’re able to share something so dear to you with someone else, and they also cherish it just as much as you do. That’s really sweet to share.
Just the connection that we had to the song, and the connection I have to the song and you know, seeing a relationship or a love experience as spilled wine makes sense to me. Especially when expressing your emotions is like a wine stain that you can’t really get out after it’s been spilled, you know? So, being very careful with your glass of wine at the party, you know? You’re not going to just spill it everywhere, because you can’t get it out of the carpet after it’s been done. People are side-eyeing you for it, you know? You don’t want to be that person. I didn’t want to be that person.

Joni Mitchell is a Canadian singer-songwriter who made waves in the 1960s-70s with her songs “Big Yellow Taxi”, along with her album, Blue.

In her October 2019 interview with Flaunt, Clairo touched on the story behind “Bags.” The author wrote:

Two teenage girls are riding in a car in Los Angeles. They’re singing along to Joni Mitchell (“Blue”, of course), driving into the timewarp of Laurel Canyon, veering between a loyal kinship they have with one another and flickers of romance—a hormonal tension at the heart of intense companionship. This was Claire Cottrill (aka Clairo)’s experience one summer, as she spent time with a girl.

Clairo recalled a moment when the pair were listening to Phoebe Bridgers‘ 2017 single “Motion Sickness”:

We were listening to  it for the 12th time in a row. I was like, ‘This song means everything to me. I wish I could write a song like this.’ And she turned to me and said, ‘You should write a Phoebe Bridgers song. You should make it about me!’ I kinda knew she meant that it should be about us, but she didn’t explicitly say it.

Following this conversation, Clairo went home and broke down the track, eventually stumbling upon the idea that formed “Bags.”

Pardon my emotions
 I should probably keep it all to myself

I feel like I’m a pretty emotional person. Even if I’m hiding my emotions, you can just read it all over my face, which is something I’m working on. Sometimes you express something and then you immediately realize that you should not have done that. That was not the right thing to do right now. They didn’t want to hear that. You shouldn’t have done that. And that’s me saying, you know, “Pardon my emotions, sorry I’m emotional. I didn’t mean to scare you, blah, blah, blah.” I should keep it all to myself and then saying, “No, you’d make fun of me.”  It’s kind of going back to how, me and this person’s relationship is. It’s very, we joke with each other. It’s really light. It’s funny. I know that she would make fun of me if I told her how I felt. She’d just be like, “What? Like, okay.” There’s something great about that. There’s something great about the fact that we could probably joke about me being like, “I’ve liked you for so long.” But I’m super happy being friends with this person. We’re just friends anyway, but it kind of just relates back to how we treated each other.

I don’t wanna be forward, I don’t wanna cut corners
 Savor this with everything I have inside of me

I think as of recently, I’ve definitely value taking things slow. I think it’s easy to get really excited about someone and your relationship, but I’ve learned that it’s a lot better to get to know them in time. Have it be this really drawn out process, I think. I really like … that’s what I love to do now. I know that’s not maybe the best, but that’s how I approach it now. I think when I was saying I don’t want to be forward, I don’t want to express my feelings so forwardly. I don’t want to scare you with my emotions even because they’re so intense.  I don’t want to cut corners. I don’t want to jump to conclusion. I don’t want to skip steps. What if we’re supposed to be friends at first, and then years from now, it’s supposed to be a certain way? There’s no way to tell, there’s no way to know. I don’t want to take things too fast for it to just burn out.

Pour your glass of wine
 Mitchell told me I should be just fine (Yeah)
 Cases under the bed

Mitchell is Joni Mitchell. So, pour your glass of wine, Mitchell. Joni Mitchell told me I’ll be just fine, cases under the bed. Spill it open, let it rush to my head. It’s an illusion to “A Case of You” by Joni Mitchell, and me and this person had been driving around listening to Joni Mitchell, but also Joni Mitchell is like a very important person to me. I just grew up listening to a lot of Joni Mitchell through my mom. That whole record is very special to me, and I think her writing is one of my absolute favorites, and you know, being able to share that with another person, driving around and listening to “A Case of You” was cool for me. It was a sweet moment. It’s like when you’re able to share something so dear to you with someone else, and they also cherish it just as much as you do. That’s really sweet to share.
Just the connection that we had to the song, and the connection I have to the song and you know, seeing a relationship or a love experience as spilled wine makes sense to me. Especially when expressing your emotions is like a wine stain that you can’t really get out after it’s been spilled, you know? So, being very careful with your glass of wine at the party, you know? You’re not going to just spill it everywhere, because you can’t get it out of the carpet after it’s been done. People are side-eyeing you for it, you know? You don’t want to be that person. I didn’t want to be that person.

Can you see me? I’m waiting for the right time
 I can’t read you, but if you want, the pleasure’s all mine

I think especially when you’re having your first experience with a girl, you know, it’s, you read into things a lot more. I think when you’re starting to explore your sexuality or you’re starting to try to figure out how girls work. It’s harder to read like how they are feeling, because they’re completely different than what you’ve ever known. And it was hard for me to read this person just because we were friends and we were joking around, and I also didn’t know if they were, they liked girls. So it’s like a lot of different layers to it. Where you know, I’m insecure. I don’t know if they like girls at all, let alone me and were really good friends. So it’s like how does that even work? How can I possibly read that in a way where I know how they feel. But it’s like saying, can you see me? I’m like, can you see me as a love interest. I’m waiting for the right time. I’m trying to, I’m sitting on the couch waiting for the right time to tell this person how I feel. I can’t read you, don’t know if you like girls. But if you want, the pleasure’s all mine. Meaning, if you did, and if you did like me, it’d be my pleasure to be that for you. It’s a really sweet song. It’s really like pure and I think that’s what I wanted to emphasize on, is like my emotions in this song and the record are very pure. And you know, they’re … It’s not about like betrayal or anything really jarring. It’s really just about these small in between moments that you blow up into one song. That you don’t really ever talk about.

Tell you how I felt
 Sugar coated melting in your mouth

in the bridge I say, “Tell you how I felt. Sugar coated melting in your mouth.” Meaning like, I tell you how I feel, and I’m being really sweet about it. I’m sugar coating everything, because I want to tell you how much I like you, and you know I’m being sweet about it. But then it turns to part in my emotions. “I should probably keep it to myself.” So it’s like this balance between, do I tell you and it’s sweet and I tell you how much you mean to me? Or is it going to turn out where I feel bad about expressing my emotions, and I should’ve never said anything to begin with? You know? So I kind of talk about what if, but I don’t think it ever really happened, which is okay. Sometimes it doesn’t need to happen.

Every minute counts
 I don’t wanna watch TV anymore, yeah
 Can you figure me out?

I think I switched from seconds to minutes just to emphasize like how much time is going by. You feel all of it when there’s that much tension in the room, I feel like, you know, at first you’re thinking about every little second going by. And then seconds turn to minutes, turn to hours of you just being confused. And wishing you knew how they felt. And you know, just as more time goes by, the more you feel like you want to tell them how you feel. And saying like, I don’t want to watch TV anymore, is also another way of me being like, you know, we’ve been sitting on the couch for hours watching random TV. I want to talk to you. Like I want to tell you how I feel. Like I wish you knew how I felt about you. There’s so much tension. They’re like, can you figure me out. Saying can’t you see how I feel about you? Can’t you see that this is how I feel? I’m only doing this to waste more time on the couch with you. I’m only watching TV with you, just to be next to you. I don’t want to be watching TV, but I’m here because you’re here.
You can call me by the name I gave you yesterday, yeah

this person and I would joke around a lot. And we would call each other like random nicknames. I don’t really remember exactly what I called them. But I think it has to do with all these little games resembles, like you know, we’re joking but is it flirty or is it just because we’re friends. But then also you know, “You can call me by the name I gave you yesterday”, is not only talking about the nicknames but eludes to “Call me by your name” because it’s about a girl, you know.

description.plain:
“Flaming Hot Cheetos” is the second track and first single from Clairo’s EP, diary 001. It acquired its name simply because Clairo was eating them when making the demo.

It’s a song about one of her past relationships, Clairo stated:

The song was sort of a struggle between one side of me trying to ‘snap out of it’, and the other side of me still wishing that things were how they used to be.

The song was produced and written by Clairo herself and it was released in June 2017.

The song was produced and written by Clairo herself and it was released in June 2017.

description.plain:
“Pretty Girl” is about a relationship Clairo had where she felt she needed to be the perfect girl for another person. Whether that was wearing makeup, doing her hair, wearing things they liked, or even changing the way she spoke. Eventually, things were broken off, and she’s better off. According to Pitchfork, “Pretty Girl” is a song about changing for a relationship and losing yourself along the way.

The song was originally recorded on GarageBand for a cassette compilation that was limited to 250 copies.

description.plain:
With its “bedroom pop” vibes and a coming-of-age lyrical style, “4EVER” is the fourth track and third single off of Clairo’s 2018 debut EP, diary 001.

Clairo herself dove into the song for Genius' video series, Verified. She mentioned how the song was born from a period of pre-college anxiety, noting the fact that she wasn’t sure if she would find better friends than those she already had at school:

I’ve made the best friends I’ve ever had at school. They are the first people I’ve met that have really wanted me to grow and want me to be different and are okay with me being weird and trying out new ideas.

I’m so affectionate, it’s gross. I just love people, I do. Especially people that I’m attracted to. I’m just a lovey, I got a tattoo of someone hugging themselves. That’s who I am.

I don’t feel like I have that much of a problem with confrontation. If it’s important to talk about, then I’ll talk about it. I’m not just gonna be like, “Oh, what are they gonna think?” I’ll just say it because at the end of the day it saves time. Yeah. I don’t know, I feel like I’m growing into someone who is confident and will say how they feel. Not too much, just enough to assert themselves.

By saying how she wants to hold this person, Clairo is not only referencing her love of affection (aforementioned), but also how she wants the person to stick with her. This is implied in the chorus, where she asks if they will “be around for me to count on”.
See you in the morning, over coffee, we’ll talk, oh

Honestly I have no idea what this came from. I thought it was funny. I don’t know sometimes when you had an experience with someone, or you fight with someone or something happens, there’s another time when you guys sit down and you’re like, “That was stupid, or that probably shouldn’t have happened, or we could have done this a different way.” I’ve had plenty of those. I don’t know, its just like over coffee we’ll talk about all the stuff we probably shouldn’t have said.

My Dunkin Donuts order is a small ice coffee with cream and sugar and a caramel swirl. The lady at the Dunkin Donuts in Syracuse sees me and then just immediately starts making it. She’s sick of seeing me. That’s my order if anyone wants to know. Just out there.
Hold you tight, squeeze you right, give you all I’ve got

I honestly think that when you’re in a relationship, most of love or most of what you’re supposed to give in a relationship is just attention. You’re supposed to pay attention to that person and make them understand that you get the little things, and you see them, and you don’t just ask them questions and it goes in one ear and out the other. I just think people want someone to appreciate them and show them that. That’s what I expect and that’s what I always give in relationships. That’s like the bare minimum, too. Just paying attention and learning about them, and shutting up for a second and learning about them. When you’re in a relationship, it’s not about you. It’s about this together but also learning about the other person, almost as much as you.
Put me in your bedroom and I’ll sing a little song

Commentary on bedroom pop. I honestly figured out that I did that after. Obviously, that was a little sexual thing that I’ve never really had anything like that in a song, so it was edgy for me. Also, the bedroom pop thing, I was like, “Oh my God, that works so well.” Everyone expects me to be this bedroom pop artist, so it’s funny like a little joke. Yeah, I figured that out after, so now I’m saying that’s why I did that, so I can seem smart.

I’m so affectionate, it’s gross. I just love people, I do. Especially people that I’m attracted to. I’m just a lovey, I got a tattoo of someone hugging themselves. That’s who I am.

I’m not just gonna be like, “Oh, what are they gonna think?” I’ll just say it because at the end of the day it saves time. Yeah. I don’t know, I feel like I’m growing into someone who is confident and will say how they feel. Not too much, just enough to assert themselves.
I knew I’d never let you get away

I want someone who’s fun and can have fun doing a lot of different things. Can go out, can not go out. I don’t know; I’m a very flexible person. I can pretty much make fun wherever I am, like make fun happen. It’s nice when other people can do that as well. You’ll be in a bad situation but you can just be together and it’s OK. That’s all I, my standards seem low.

Some things just never seem to fade
 I’m thinking about how we were on our first date

The song obviously gets relationshippy because that’s what I always do. If we’re saying the song is about a person then … When you first meet someone and start a relationship everything’s real exciting and fun in the beginning. You want it to stay that way, especially if you’re going into a relationship you want it to be exciting and fun and mysterious the whole time.

It’s scary when you dive into a relationship and you don’t know if its always going to be that way. No one really wants it to change. No one wants it to go to shit. No one wants it to go sour and that’s a question I feel like people ask themselves all the time. Realationships are like, “Oh shit hopefully I like this person five years from now.” I don’t know I was asking myself that like okay. I guess that’s also part of getting a relationship, you take that risk.

Is it ever gonna change? Am I gonna feel this way forever?
 Are you gonna be around for me to count on?

When, I know I can count on someone when they’re loyal to me and they care about me, they check in on me, they make sure I feel needed, and I do the same—when that’s happening, I feel like I can count on someone, and I feel like they’re important to me and close to me. Sometimes that changes when your surroundings change, but I’m lucky to have some friends from home that have been there from the very beginning and nothing has changed because we’re tight. That’s cool, I want to keep having that.

Some things just aren’t that simple
 You called me wondering why I changed

I think just how I felt. I think, it’s hard to know what the song’s about because it can be applied to a lot of different things. But I think I was talking about college and a relationship. So things aren’t that simple when you aren’t really sure where you want to be placed in the world. I wasn’t 100% confident about any of my music or any of my skills and I was going to college for music business. I didn’t know if I was going to be successful with that. It’s hard to, it was hard to pinpoint where I was really at because nothing was happening with music, I also started going to college, and I was like, “Boys.” Lots of different things, it’s not simple.

Also, the bedroom pop thing, I was like, “Oh my God, that works so well.” Everyone expects me to be this bedroom pop artist, so it’s funny like a little joke. Yeah, I figured that out after, so now I’m saying that’s why I did that, so I can seem smart.

Clairo references her reputation, and personal rise to fame, as a bedroom pop singer.

The thematic focus of 4EVER encapsulates the characteristics of bedroom pop Clairo has built her reputation on; ‘contemplative lyrics, ambient sounds’ and ‘authenticity’.

description.plain:
“Amoeba” is perhaps the most groovy track from Clairo’s sophomore album Sling. Amoebas are unicellular organisms, and the noun comes from the greek amoibe which means “change, alteration, exchange”. As stated by the singer, the theme of the song is in fact changing her priorities:

 It’s about prioritizing the wrong things. I’d go out on tour and forget to call my family and my friends, forget to eat, then come home and realize my hair’s falling out because I’m not taking care of myself.

On August 6, 2021, Rolling Stone posted a video of Clairo and producer Jack Antonoff breaking down the track, explaining some of the lyrics and production.

annotations: Have your toes touch the lack of cement

This line may reference the recording process of Sling, which was recorded in Allaire Studios in a mountain top. It references the lack of cement in the mountain and the radical change from the city life.

Aren’t you glad that you reside in a Hell and in disguise?
 Nobody yet everything, a pool to shed your memory

Reference to Lethe, one of the five rivers of the underworld of Hades. Also known as the “Ameles potamos” (river of unmindfulness), the Lethe flowed around the cave of Hypnos and through the Underworld where all those who drank from it experienced complete forgetfulness.
This could mean Clairo feels like she deserves to be in “hell” because of her actions. As she said: “The main meaning of [‘Amoeba’] was – in a weird way, it’s me scolding myself about my actions…”
You’re not as good as what your mama’s sewn

This explains Claire’s feelings toward this person she’s become. Throughout the album Cottrill expresses her feelings towards motherhood & how her mother had done so much for her growing up.

The conversations I had with my mom about motherhood, and the things she sacrificed for us, are really important to me.

-Clairo via The Guardian

This line is Claire looking back on that, and how she’s turned into someone worse than her mother’s raised her.

You haven’t called your family twice
 I can hope tonight goes differently
 But I show up to the party just to leave

During an interview with ABC in July 2021, Clairo offered further insight into the meaning of these lines:

You haven’t called your family in two weeks, you’re just going to parties, trying to impress the wrong person and putting your energy in the wrong places. Being able to acknowledge that and change that [about myself] was a big part of Sling. It was really just about seeing my own thoughts, questioning why they were happening and how I can change them and better myself.

Gather to one corner of the woods
 Echo chambers inside a neighborhood

Echo chambers occur when the same perspective or the same ideas are repeated over and over. Claire recorded Sling with Jack Antonoff at Allaire Studios, a picturesque mountain-top-located studio in Upstate New York, far from the city’s noise echo chambers, and this would have allowed her to focus without distractions.

Another interpretation is that Clairo metaphorically gathered her thoughts whilst indoors due to the COVID-19 pandemic, which began in early 2020.  Sling features themes such as motherhood, settling down and mental health, and in an interview with Apple Music, she revealed that she wouldn’t have thought about such themes for a long time if it weren’t for the pandemic:

I looked at my mom very differently, because I was able to see all the sacrifices she’s made for me […] How I feel has been really […] uplifting and has really helped my work as well. Those thoughts and feelings have crept into the songs as well.

description.plain:
“Hello” is the first collaboration between American singer-songwriter Clairo and Irish rapper Rejjie Snow. Clairo sings about a passionate romance strained by physical and emotional separation, while Rejjie reminisces on the relationship’s origins.

The self-produced instrumental features a simple two-chord synth loop and a bouncy drum beat, evocative of Clairo’s previous instrumental for her SoundCloud hit “Flaming Hot Cheetos.”

You’re just one click away, click away, click away
 From something real or fake,
The speaker is saying that their partner is a text or a call away from something that could turn out to be developmental in their relationship or just a good time.
You’re just one click away

The speaker and their partner are either in a long distance relationship or aren’t with eachother at the moment. “you’re just one click” away could reference a booty call or just simply a visit to eachother.

You’re so close, and yet so far
 I wonder how you look when you’re in the dark

I think Clairo is talking about a long – distance situation in which the other person means so much to her and is close to her heart, yet is still so far away. She also talks about how she wants to see this person in a different way than how she normally sees them, being that you typically cannot see in the dark.
Click away

PROPOSED SUGGESTION:

I think it’s more about long distance. Love can sometimes feel very faint and come in waves when it’s a long distance relationship. Clairo is struggling if this love is really ‘'real’'

Taste like RiRi, taste like Bey
 Bought you Fenty, took his place

Rejjie is saying that his girl has expensive taste. He references Rihanna, “Riri,” and Beyoncé, “Bey,” who are known for having extravagant lifestyles. Fenty Beauty is a makeup brand created by Rihanna.
Hot jump, skip rope, twenty-three years old

The number 23 is repeated over and over in Rejji Snow’s album ‘Dear Annie’, stressing the importance of this number to him. There is even a song on the album called 23.

Referring to how different their music tastes are, comparing MF DOOM’s experimental rap to Drake’s mainstream R&B.
